body:
Thank you! that would be super helpful.

I think changing the `d.ts` alone is not sufficient since TypeScript does not allow for a constant to be exported that is simply named `default`. e.g. `declare const default = function` does not work. The workaround solution we use is:

```ts
import _template from '@babel/template';

// Babel is a CJS package and uses `default` as named binding (`exports.default =`).
// https://github.com/babel/babel/issues/15269.
const template = (_template as any)['default'] as typeof _template
```

For anyone using esbuild, you can add this plugin to allow both default and named imports in esm:

```js
const babelDefaultImportPlugin = {
  name: 'babel-default-import',
  setup: build => {
    build.onResolve({ filter: /^@babel\/(traverse|generator)$/ }, args => {
      return { path: args.path, namespace: 'babel-default-import' };
    });

    build.onLoad({ filter: /.*/, namespace: 'babel-default-import' }, args => {
      return {
        resolveDir: 'node_modules',
        contents: `import module from '${args.path}/lib/index.js';
          export default module.default ?? module;
          export * from '${args.path}/lib/index.js';`,
      };
    });
  },
};

esbuild.build({
  // ...
  plugins: [babelDefaultImportPlugin],
})
```

> we don't maintain the .d.ts for @babel/generator

But it's not d.ts issue. I can place simple js file from cookbook:
```javascript
import generate from "@babel/generator";
import parser from "@babel/parser";

const code = `function square(n) {
  return n * n;
}`;

const ast = parser.parse(code);

const output = generate(ast, {}, code);
console.log(output);
```
Run `node test.mjs` and oops:
```
file:///tmp/test.mjs:10
const output = generate(ast, {}, code);
               ^

TypeError: generate is not a function
    at file:///Volumes/work/fingular/aha/test.mjs:10:16
    at ModuleJob.run (node:internal/modules/esm/module_job:271:25)
    at async onImport.tracePromise.__proto__ (node:internal/modules/esm/loader:547:26)
    at async asyncRunEntryPointWithESMLoader (node:internal/modules/run_main:116:5)

Node.js v22.12.0
```

Moreover, this usage is documented, as @Rounak-stha mentions in the [official docs](https://github.com/jamiebuilds/babel-handbook/blob/master/translations/en/plugin-handbook.md#visiting).
So it looks like a bug. Maybe it's a bug in node.js esm implementation... but it should be much easier to fix in one module than in node.js engine.
Why can't we fix it in babel 7? Why should the whole community have to deal with dirty hacks for another year or two until babel 8 can be adopted?

It seems to me that this can be fixed very easily... It's enough to add another named export, it can be done without breaking backwards compatibility.
